Had a leftover brisket in our freezer from@theblindgoathtx move-out, so @suhpremeleader decided to rub it with ground Sichuan peppercorns, MSG, and salt & pepper before smoking it Texas BBQ-style 🥩 I was making classic southern collard greens to go with the brisket using stock I’d made from our leftover Thanksgiving turkey carcass, and at the last minute, decided to put a bún bò Huê’ twist on it. I added lemongrass, fish sauce, shrimp paste, lemon juice, and chile oil 🥬 The dishes turned out great with just a hint of Chinese and Vietnamese flavors complementing the classic southern fare. Just random Sunday home cookin’. Sometimes this is how new recipe ideas are born.

@lovie821 and I thought it would be fun to do a tasting of the wines and cheeses served at the recent White House State dinner for French President Emmanuel Macron. Here’s what we tried:
🧀 Cypress Grove Humboldt Fog soft-ripened goat cheese from California - aged 60 days with a ribbon of edible vegetable ash through the middle, World Cheese Awards Ggold winner in 2014 and 2018)
🧀 Deer Creek The Doe cheddar from Wisconsin - we couldn’t find The Fawn served at the State dinner so got The Doe instead; marbled with Madagascar bourbon vanilla bean
🧀 Rogue Creamery Rogue River blue from Oregon - cave-aged 9–11 months and wrapped in organic Syrah grape leaves that have been soaked in pear spirits,  limited released each year on the autumn equinox; the first American cheese to be named the World Champion at World Cheese Awards in 2019
🍷  Roederer Estate brut rosé, Mendocino County
🍷 Newton Napa Valley unfiltered chardonnay 2018, Napa Valley
Plus a friend brought some off-menu aged Wisconsin cheddar and a bottle of organic wine. Life is nice.

2022 has come to an end so thought I’d do a year-end reflection 🤔 
It was a tough year—friends got diagnosed with serious illnesses, other friends had loved ones pass away, and my own dad died. Running 3.5 businesses, closing one restaurant location while building two new ones…But there were some great moments too, like getting nominated for a James Beard Award, making guest appearances on both Top Chef and MasterChef, and doing more speaking engagements and events after a major drought during the COVID pandemic. And with 2023 around the corner, I’m leaning hard into hope. I’m optimistic for the opening of @theblindgoathtx in a new space and the opening of @stuffedbellyco. I’m looking forward to expanding my professional horizon with the James Beard Women’s Entrepreneurial Leadership program where I’ll learn how to grow my restaurant businesses alongside other women in the industry. In the civil service realm, I just joined the American Culinary Corps through the U.S. Department of State in partnership with the James Beard Foundation to help further culinary diplomacy in the United States and abroad, and I’m working with the U.S. Embassy Vietnam to do another tour as a culinary arts envoy in 2023. In the non-profit sector, I will serve on the Board of Trustees of Helen Keller International and in the Chef Corps for World Central Kitchen.
Reflecting on what’s in store for 2023 reminds me that I am blessed, and with these privileges comes the responsibility to serve my community, country, and world with my time and talents.
May you close out 2022 with peace in your heart and start 2023 with hope and optimism, too. Happy new year, stay safe, and be well, everyone! 💚🎉🎇

Chúc mừng năm mới! Happy Lunar New Year! 🎇 This is the first Tết without both of my parents, so I felt the need to make an ancestral altar for them filled with all the goodies— bánh chừng, giò lụa, nem chùa, my homemade xôi mặn, Chinese egg tarts, dried fruit & candy, and the bottle of Courvoisier that my dad bought on my 4th birthday in May 1983. He’d told me he was saving it to drink on my wedding day but instead, he gave it to @suhpremeleader and me after we got married. Now I’m offering it back to my parents to imbibe in the afterlife 🥃 This is my first bàn thờ I’ve ever done by myself. Hope Mom and Dad are proud!🧧 Wishing you all a joyous, prosperous, and healthy Year of the Cat/Rabbit! 🐱🐇

When I was about 8 years old, my parents used to put cha cha, rhumba, and tango music on the cassette player Saturday mornings and boogie around the house 💃🕺🏻 Many years later when my mom passed, my dad began taking ballroom dancing lessons. He accumulated trophies over the years for different competitions, and I remember watching a VHS of him doing the foxtrot with his dance partner 🏆 Because of these memories, I’ve always wanted to learn to dance, just like my parents. Felt like cooking so I made Texas beef chili with dried ancho and guajillo peppers + cornbread with aged cheddar, cream cheese, scallion, and actual kernels of corn 🐮🌽 Growing up, the only cornbread I knew was the dry, boring ones that came on our school cafeteria lunch trays. The other is hot egg coffee which reminds me of a Vietnamese eggy cappuccino in format and a mash-up of espresso and eggnog in taste. Raw egg yolk gets blended with the condensed milk to form a thick cream that gets added to the coffee, adding a richness to the beverage 🥚

Growing up, bánh rán was one of the snacks my dad ate often. Some people refer to it as a “Vietnamese donut ball.” It’s kind of a crispy ball of dough that gets stuffed with different fillings and fried so it’s crispy on the outside and a little chewy on the inside. Now in Hanoi, I got to try bánh rán mặn for the first time. Instead of being coated with sesame seeds and filled with sweet beans the way my dad always ate them, I tried one that was savory and filled with pork and wood ear mushroom. So delicious! #hanoistreetfood #Hanoistreeteats
